he essays trace the relationship, often negative, between Arthurian chivalry and the Grail ethos. Whereas most of the contributors reflect on the popularity of the Grail quest, several examine the comparative rarity of the Grail in certain literatures and define the elaboration of quest motifs severed from the Grail material. An appendix to the volume offers a filmography that includes all the cinematic treatments of the Grail, either as central theme or minor motif. This book will appeal to students, scholars, and general readers fascinated by the Arthurian and Grail legends. CONTRIBUTORS: NORRIS J. LACY, ANTONIO FURTADO, WILL HASTY, RICHARD TRACHSLER, MARIANNE E. KALINKE, MARTINE MEUWESE, DAVID F. JOHNSON, PHILLIP BOARDMAN, CAROLINE D. ECKHARDT, P.J.C. FIELD, JAMES P. CARLEY, RICHARD BARBER, KEVIN J. HARTY  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aArthurian Literature.  aChivalry.  aFilmography.  aGrail Ethos.  aGrail Quest.  aQuest Motifs.1 aBarber, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoardman, Phillip C, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoardman, Phillip C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarley, James P, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarley, James P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEckhardt, Caroline D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEckhardt, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aField, P.J.C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aField, Peter J C, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFurtado, Antonio L., econtributor.4c